Putin’s Forces Attack Ukraine

Ukraine’s government said it faced “a full-scale attack from multiple directions.” World leaders condemned President Vladimir Putin’s actions.
Published Feb. 23, 2022 Updated March 10, 2022, 6:23 a.m. ET

Follow our live news updates on the Russia - Ukraine war.
Image Damaged radar arrays and other equipment at a Ukrainian military facility outside Mariupol on Thursday.
Damaged radar arrays and other equipment at a Ukrainian military facility outside Mariupol on Thursday. Credit... Sergei Grits/Associated Press
Nate Cohn
Feb. 25, 2022, 5:00 p.m. ET
Feb. 25, 2022, 5:00 p.m. ET

Nate Cohn
Before the invasion, polls showed Americans were wary of major U.S. involvement in Ukraine.
Image American troops were deployed to Poland earlier this month.
American troops were deployed to Poland earlier this month. Credit... Kenny Holston for The New York Times

While Americans are still digesting the news of Russia’s invasion of Ukraine, public opinion surveys in the run-up to the conflict found that voters were divided over just how far the United States should go to support Ukraine — and what costs they would be willing to bear.

The surveys depicted a nation that was apprehensive about becoming entangled in another armed conflict but nonetheless backed at least some American response to Russian aggression.

Over all, 52 percent of Americans said that the U.S. should have a “minor role,” in the situation in Ukraine, while 26 percent supported a “major role” and 20 percent argued for no role at all, according to a survey completed Monday by The Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research.

More than two-thirds of voters said they supported additional sanctions against Russia, according to a Reuters poll , while nearly two-thirds said they opposed sending American troops.

The results are largely consistent with the steps proposed by the Biden Administration, which moved to impose harsh sanctions against Russia while ruling out American military intervention.

Even so, the surveys offered few signs that the public was poised to rally behind Mr. Biden during an international crisis. Just 43 percent of voters approved of his handling of his relationship with Russia, according to the Reuters poll. The tally closely mirrored his overall approval rating, suggesting that attitudes about his handling of Russia may reflect general attitudes about his presidency more than any specific views of his foreign policy.

The surveys were taken before the Russian invasion into Ukraine and should be interpreted with caution. The findings only represent a baseline measure of where the public stood before the conflict, and attitudes might change quickly with new developments and sustained media coverage. It could be several more days before most pollsters complete surveys taken entirely after the Russian invasion.

While the reality of a large-scale invasion might be expected to boost public support for measures to respond to Russian aggression, the onset of conflict creates risks for the Biden administration as well.

The Reuters poll found that only about half of Americans backed sanctions against Russia if it would mean higher gas prices — as seems likely — even though more than two-thirds of voters said they supported increased sanctions in general.

Even before any economic fallout from the conflict, most voters gave Mr. Biden poor ratings for his handling of the economy, inflation and gas prices. Voters have ranked inflation and the economy among the most important issues facing the country in surveys taken over the last several months.

And although few Americans blame Mr. Biden for the crisis — only a mere 25 percent of Republicans blamed Mr. Biden in the Reuters poll — the Russian invasion may contribute to a sense of an increasingly dangerous and chaotic world, beyond Mr. Biden’s ability to handle.
