Carlotta Gall
Ukraine asks Turkey to close the Bosporus and Dardanelles straits to warships.
Image
A Russian Navy ship traveling through the Bosporus en route to the Black Sea this month. Credit... Emrah Gurel/Associated Press

ISTANBUL — Ukraine’s ambassador to Ankara called for Turkey to close its airspace and to forbid passage through the Bosporus and Dardanelles straits to warships.

The straits are the only way for ships to transit from the Black Sea, where Russia maintains a naval fleet, to the Mediterranean.

In a live televised news conference from the Ukrainian embassy in Ankara, Turkey’s capital, Ambassador Vasyl Bodnar said Ukraine had made an official request to the Turkish government. He also called for support from Turkey for sanctions against Russia, and for military and humanitarian assistance and help for Ukrainian citizens in Turkey.

“Right now all the masks are off,” he said. “Right now we are at war. We call all the world to take up and prevent that aggression. Today Ukraine is protecting your safety too.”

President Recep Tayyip Erdogan of Turkey, who visited Ukraine earlier this month , began a security meeting with senior security officials Thursday morning, the presidential palace announced in a statement.

Turkey is a member of NATO but also maintains economic and military industry ties with Russia. The two countries are on opposing sides in two Middle Eastern wars, in Syria and Libya , and in the conflict between Azerbaijan and Armenia in the South Caucasus.
